00:00:02.009 --> 00:00:07.390
ANNOUNCER: It is my pleasure
to welcome our illustrious

00:00:07.390 --> 00:00:07.900
speaker.

00:00:07.900 --> 00:00:12.950
And in particular, my church
pastor, Father Jack McClure

00:00:12.950 --> 00:00:16.329
from Most Holy
Redeemer in the Castro,

00:00:16.329 --> 00:00:17.984
who will be
moderating and helping

00:00:17.984 --> 00:00:19.150
move the conversation along.

00:00:19.150 --> 00:00:21.740
So I'm going to kick
it off for y'all.

00:00:21.740 --> 00:00:22.939
JACK MCCLURE: Thank you.

00:00:22.939 --> 00:00:24.480
Thank you, everybody,
for being here.

00:00:24.480 --> 00:00:26.354
Thank you, Matthew for
coming and joining us.

00:00:26.354 --> 00:00:29.520
We're looking forward to hearing
your perspectives and how

00:00:29.520 --> 00:00:32.890
you came to them and sharing
with the group gathered here

00:00:32.890 --> 00:00:36.330
today ways that we
all can think with you

00:00:36.330 --> 00:00:38.560
and how our thinking might
need to change, as well,

00:00:38.560 --> 00:00:40.280
or we'll be invited to.

00:00:40.280 --> 00:00:41.740
So, as a Roman
Catholic priest, I'm

00:00:41.740 --> 00:00:44.320
excited to listen
to how you present.

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:48.120
Because it's an important
topic in my church, right now.

00:00:48.120 --> 00:00:51.750
And my understanding is key,
so I join with this group

00:00:51.750 --> 00:00:53.490
here in looking forward
to your comment.

00:00:53.490 --> 00:00:56.140
So thank you for being here.

00:00:56.140 --> 00:00:56.690
Welcome.

00:00:56.690 --> 00:00:57.150
MATTHEW VINES: Well,
thank you so much.

00:00:57.150 --> 00:00:58.983
JACK MCCLURE: Tell us
about you a little bit

00:00:58.983 --> 00:01:01.310
so that we all know how
you came to the positions

00:01:01.310 --> 00:01:03.219
that you're holding,
and enlighten us.

00:01:03.219 --> 00:01:04.260
MATTHEW VINES: All right.

00:01:04.260 --> 00:01:07.370
Well, first I want to say thank
you to Raymond for inviting me

00:01:07.370 --> 00:01:12.540
and the whole LGBT Pride
Week team for coordinating.

00:01:12.540 --> 00:01:13.735
I really appreciate that.

00:01:13.735 --> 00:01:14.860
It is wonderful to be here.

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:23.340
So you want some
of my backstory,

00:01:23.340 --> 00:01:25.250
in terms of how I
got to this point?

00:01:25.250 --> 00:01:26.833
JACK MCCLURE: I
thought in your book--

00:01:26.833 --> 00:01:29.550
I got to look at your book
and to read some parts of it.

00:01:29.550 --> 00:01:31.550
I thought it was very
interesting, the beginning

00:01:31.550 --> 00:01:33.930
part, when you decided
you needed to come out,

00:01:33.930 --> 00:01:36.975
to go home and share with
your family and your parents.

00:01:36.975 --> 00:01:37.850
MATTHEW VINES: Right.

00:01:37.850 --> 00:01:43.060
So that was the fall 2009 that
I first acknowledged to myself

00:01:43.060 --> 00:01:44.190
that I was gay.

00:01:44.190 --> 00:01:45.700
The reason why
that was difficult

00:01:45.700 --> 00:01:50.060
was because I am from
Kansas, from Wichita, Kansas

00:01:50.060 --> 00:01:53.300
and grew up in a conservative,
evangelical Presbyterian

00:01:53.300 --> 00:01:56.080
church, there,
where there was just

00:01:56.080 --> 00:02:02.620
no open conversation around
being gay or anything

00:02:02.620 --> 00:02:04.000
other than straight.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:06.520
We actually had a good
friend who had grown up,

00:02:06.520 --> 00:02:08.520
just a couple years older
than me in our church,

00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:11.161
was really well regarded
until he came out

00:02:11.161 --> 00:02:12.410
his sophomore year of college.

00:02:12.410 --> 00:02:14.700
And then it was like
he had been erased

00:02:14.700 --> 00:02:16.290
from the memory
of the community.

00:02:16.290 --> 00:02:18.530
And nobody wanted to
talk about him anymore.

00:02:18.530 --> 00:02:22.440
It was very frustrating
to witness that.

00:02:22.440 --> 00:02:25.019
But also, those
are all the sorts

00:02:25.019 --> 00:02:27.060
of things that made it
difficult for me to accept

00:02:27.060 --> 00:02:28.060
the fact that I was gay.

00:02:28.060 --> 00:02:31.250
Because my parents would
not be OK with that.

00:02:31.250 --> 00:02:34.070
So many of our closest
family friends from church

00:02:34.070 --> 00:02:35.890
would not be OK with that.

00:02:35.890 --> 00:02:38.490
But if you are gay,
you kind of have

00:02:38.490 --> 00:02:39.695
to deal with it, eventually.

00:02:39.695 --> 00:02:43.760
Well, you don't have to, but
it's going to eat away at you,

00:02:43.760 --> 00:02:45.530
pretty significantly,
if you don't.

00:02:45.530 --> 00:02:50.656
So it helped me a lot, going
away to Harvard for college.

00:02:50.656 --> 00:02:52.780
I think we have some-- do
we have some Harvard 2012

00:02:52.780 --> 00:02:54.544
people in the house?

00:02:54.544 --> 00:02:56.210
I know we have at
least one Harvard 2012

00:02:56.210 --> 00:02:59.690
person in the house--
who's not raising his hand.

00:02:59.690 --> 00:03:00.190
That's OK.

00:03:03.620 --> 00:03:08.090
Yeah, so Harvard is a very, very
different place from Kansas.

00:03:08.090 --> 00:03:11.170
I don't know if
people knew that.

00:03:11.170 --> 00:03:12.530
But they're slightly different.

00:03:12.530 --> 00:03:14.840
And one of the biggest
differences-- I mean,

00:03:14.840 --> 00:03:16.400
one of these
differences is that it

00:03:16.400 --> 00:03:20.380
was really cold and depressing.

00:03:20.380 --> 00:03:22.870
But apart from that-- I think
that's just an East Coast

00:03:22.870 --> 00:03:26.820
thing-- there was much more
openness to LGBT students

00:03:26.820 --> 00:03:28.840
on campus, which was awesome.

00:03:28.840 --> 00:03:31.810
And that helped me
to really experience

00:03:31.810 --> 00:03:34.360
what life could look
like as a gay person,

00:03:34.360 --> 00:03:36.060
and be able to
actually see that it's

00:03:36.060 --> 00:03:40.420
possible to have a dignified
future as a gay person.

00:03:40.420 --> 00:03:44.670
Which is something that-- we
all read the same headlines

00:03:44.670 --> 00:03:48.212
in the newspapers about gay
rights and things like that.

00:03:48.212 --> 00:03:50.170
But the way that you
experience those headlines

00:03:50.170 --> 00:03:55.140
is shaped very much by your
immediate family and community

00:03:55.140 --> 00:03:56.180
context.

00:03:56.180 --> 00:03:59.680
So even though I knew that gay
marriage was being legalized

00:03:59.680 --> 00:04:02.990
in different places, I
still had no direct examples

00:04:02.990 --> 00:04:06.630
in my life of people who are
gay, where that did not result

00:04:06.630 --> 00:04:11.870
in complete ostracisation,
or ostracism, or rejection,

00:04:11.870 --> 00:04:14.810
or stigma attached to them.

00:04:14.810 --> 00:04:17.029
So growing up in
the community I did,

00:04:17.029 --> 00:04:19.439
if you wanted to be a
successful, respectable person,

00:04:19.439 --> 00:04:20.980
being gay was
incompatible with that.

00:04:20.980 --> 00:04:23.000
Now, obviously, that's
just not true in so much

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:24.360
of the rest of the country.

00:04:24.360 --> 00:04:27.790
But not only is that
steeped in your community,

00:04:27.790 --> 00:04:29.990
it's also steeped in
your understanding of God

00:04:29.990 --> 00:04:34.840
and of faith and
Christianity, if you grew up

00:04:34.840 --> 00:04:36.860
in a Christian environment.

00:04:36.860 --> 00:04:40.020
So the barriers to sort
of reconsidering that

00:04:40.020 --> 00:04:41.290
are really steep.

00:04:41.290 --> 00:04:43.010
But being at a
place like Harvard

00:04:43.010 --> 00:04:46.270
was extremely helpful
for me in being

00:04:46.270 --> 00:04:50.110
able to process some
of these questions.

00:04:50.110 --> 00:04:51.950
First, at an impersonal level.

00:04:51.950 --> 00:04:53.750
I joined the only
groups at Harvard

00:04:53.750 --> 00:04:56.810
that would not be OK
with it if I came out,

00:04:56.810 --> 00:04:59.060
which were like the conservative
Christian ministries.

00:04:59.060 --> 00:05:02.720
Because that's where I found the
most continuity with my faith

00:05:02.720 --> 00:05:03.840
community from back home.

00:05:03.840 --> 00:05:05.631
And those were some of
the best communities

00:05:05.631 --> 00:05:08.770
that I found it
school, actually.

00:05:08.770 --> 00:05:10.800
And so, the first year
that I was at school,

00:05:10.800 --> 00:05:12.764
I really sort of asking
a lot more questions

00:05:12.764 --> 00:05:14.430
to other people in
the group about-- I'm

00:05:14.430 --> 00:05:16.920
not really sure I agree with
what this group is saying

00:05:16.920 --> 00:05:18.336
and what the church
I'd grew up in

00:05:18.336 --> 00:05:20.250
is saying about gay marriage.

00:05:20.250 --> 00:05:23.120
And so, we had some informal
gatherings about it.

00:05:23.120 --> 00:05:23.809
I read some.

00:05:23.809 --> 00:05:26.100
We had some discussions that
helped me to really change

00:05:26.100 --> 00:05:28.700
my mind on the issue.

00:05:28.700 --> 00:05:30.400
At that point, it
wasn't a total 180.

00:05:30.400 --> 00:05:32.250
I already felt, very
strongly, like there

00:05:32.250 --> 00:05:36.280
was a-- like I couldn't accept
what I had been raised with,

00:05:36.280 --> 00:05:40.120
for just basic Christian
principles of justice

00:05:40.120 --> 00:05:42.310
and all of those things.

00:05:42.310 --> 00:05:44.450
But I still didn't know
how to articulate that

00:05:44.450 --> 00:05:47.667
from the Bible-based
standpoint that I grew up with.

00:05:47.667 --> 00:05:50.000
And so, being able to learn
a little bit more about that

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:56.210
helped me to decide that I was
convinced that LGBT issues were

00:05:56.210 --> 00:05:57.350
justice issues.

00:05:57.350 --> 00:05:59.766
And that there was something
I wanted to advocate for.

00:05:59.766 --> 00:06:02.390
And it was only after that point
that, then, I could ask myself

00:06:02.390 --> 00:06:04.420
whether or not I was gay,
which I wasn't very thrilled

00:06:04.420 --> 00:06:06.628
about-- even though I didn't
think there was anything

00:06:06.628 --> 00:06:09.770
wrong with being gay anymore--
just because I didn't want

00:06:09.770 --> 00:06:13.150
to deal with the potential
loss of so many relationships.

00:06:13.150 --> 00:06:15.550
So I ended up taking
a semester off school,

00:06:15.550 --> 00:06:18.060
going home, coming
out to my parents.

00:06:18.060 --> 00:06:20.770
And then just working
through the conversation

00:06:20.770 --> 00:06:24.210
around the Bible and same-sex
relationships with them.

00:06:24.210 --> 00:06:26.975
They were not thrilled
that I was gay.

00:06:26.975 --> 00:06:29.380
And they were also
totally shocked.

00:06:29.380 --> 00:06:31.884
It just wasn't within their--
very few of my friends

00:06:31.884 --> 00:06:32.800
were all that shocked.

00:06:32.800 --> 00:06:36.900
But it wasn't within their-- the
realm of possibility for them,

00:06:36.900 --> 00:06:39.410
because they figured if
you raised your child well,

00:06:39.410 --> 00:06:41.014
then they're not
going to be gay.

00:06:41.014 --> 00:06:42.430
Which we know is
not how it works.

00:06:42.430 --> 00:06:42.780
JACK MCCLURE: Right.

00:06:42.780 --> 00:06:45.130
MATTHEW VINES: But that's how
a lot of Christian parents

00:06:45.130 --> 00:06:47.620
sort of approach it or
avoid thinking about it.

00:06:47.620 --> 00:06:49.620
But they end up
changing their minds.

00:06:49.620 --> 00:06:51.940
And for my dad, in
particular, studying the Bible

00:06:51.940 --> 00:06:55.010
and same-sex
relationships was pivotal

00:06:55.010 --> 00:06:56.425
for him changing his mind.

00:06:56.425 --> 00:06:57.550
And so, a lot people then--

00:06:57.550 --> 00:07:00.100
JACK MCCLURE: I like how
you did that in the book.

00:07:00.100 --> 00:07:02.530
Along that line,
what let you then

00:07:02.530 --> 00:07:07.370
move from-- I think I gathered
that his probing and his

00:07:07.370 --> 00:07:10.000
looking in the scriptures
with you-- see,

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:13.400
that's a tradition that your
particular faith community

00:07:13.400 --> 00:07:15.670
would have, not
always the tradition

00:07:15.670 --> 00:07:18.050
that some here are a part of.

00:07:18.050 --> 00:07:22.000
So biblically based,
then you went into strive

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:23.970
and to delve more deeply.

00:07:23.970 --> 00:07:26.870
How did you move from that
place with your father

00:07:26.870 --> 00:07:28.740
and you coming to
that understanding?

00:07:28.740 --> 00:07:31.140
What let you get underneath
the things that have let

00:07:31.140 --> 00:07:32.690
you come to the conclusions?

00:07:32.690 --> 00:07:35.950
But I think you state, very
interestingly, in your book,

00:07:35.950 --> 00:07:36.945
how did you get there?

00:07:36.945 --> 00:07:38.820
MATTHEW VINES: Well, so
it's a couple things.

00:07:38.820 --> 00:07:42.030
One, growing up in a
Protestant evangelical home,

00:07:42.030 --> 00:07:44.420
sola scriptura is
kind of the mantra--

00:07:44.420 --> 00:07:45.170
JACK MCCLURE: Mhm.

00:07:45.170 --> 00:07:47.400
And say what that means.

00:07:47.400 --> 00:07:50.210
MATTHEW VINES: Only
scripture-- scripture alone

00:07:50.210 --> 00:07:56.760
is how we learn about God and
how we discern what is true.

00:07:56.760 --> 00:07:58.360
In a sense that,
specifically, as

00:07:58.360 --> 00:08:01.640
in opposition to
the Catholic Church,

00:08:01.640 --> 00:08:04.890
and the idea that you
figure out what's true about

00:08:04.890 --> 00:08:06.370
scripture through
the magisterium.

00:08:06.370 --> 00:08:07.870
Which I got through
the magisterium,

00:08:07.870 --> 00:08:10.181
instead, know-- just going
back to the principles

00:08:10.181 --> 00:08:12.722
of the Reformation-- we're going
to figure it out on our own.

00:08:12.722 --> 00:08:15.240
Now, obviously that
spawned several 10s

00:08:15.240 --> 00:08:16.510
of thousands of denominations.

00:08:16.510 --> 00:08:17.614
But it also--

00:08:17.614 --> 00:08:20.030
JACK MCCLURE: And relative to
that, that's important to us

00:08:20.030 --> 00:08:22.960
here, from a Roman
Catholic-- or some

00:08:22.960 --> 00:08:28.180
of your more ritualistic
celebrations of church--

00:08:28.180 --> 00:08:32.130
would see the sacrament
as in combination

00:08:32.130 --> 00:08:34.950
with the magisterium, is
the way we would say that.

00:08:34.950 --> 00:08:37.299
And the Protestant
tradition would

00:08:37.299 --> 00:08:40.304
say, in scripture alone-- sola
scriptura, as you called it.

00:08:40.304 --> 00:08:41.179
MATTHEW VINES: Right.

00:08:41.179 --> 00:08:43.179
JACK MCCLURE: In
scripture alone,

00:08:43.179 --> 00:08:46.340
and so actually, it
seems to me that we're

00:08:46.340 --> 00:08:49.680
kind of moving toward a better
understanding, in the Roman

00:08:49.680 --> 00:08:51.640
Catholic side, of scripture.

00:08:51.640 --> 00:08:55.380
Because we had not studied it
as people, as the people of God.

00:08:55.380 --> 00:08:57.830
Our priests had and theologians.

00:08:57.830 --> 00:08:59.730
But you got into some
of that study, which

00:08:59.730 --> 00:09:02.230
I think has become very,
very important to you,

00:09:02.230 --> 00:09:04.060
to understand that
which is underneath some

00:09:04.060 --> 00:09:05.160
of the scriptural texts.

00:09:05.160 --> 00:09:06.049
Is that--

00:09:06.049 --> 00:09:06.840
MATTHEW VINES: Yes.

00:09:06.840 --> 00:09:10.490
And part of the reason why that
study is possible, or possible

00:09:10.490 --> 00:09:12.270
to be more effective
within my context,

00:09:12.270 --> 00:09:16.870
is because, theoretically,
at least, with Protestants,

00:09:16.870 --> 00:09:19.571
all you have to do
is convince someone

00:09:19.571 --> 00:09:21.320
of a different
interpretation of the text.

00:09:21.320 --> 00:09:21.760
JACK MCCLURE: Exactly.

00:09:21.760 --> 00:09:23.520
MATTHEW VINES: And
that is all, in theory,

00:09:23.520 --> 00:09:26.855
that is required in order to
change beliefs and then change

00:09:26.855 --> 00:09:27.355
doctrines.

00:09:27.355 --> 00:09:30.860
Now, obviously, there are
natural, institutional hurdles,

00:09:30.860 --> 00:09:31.670
as well.

00:09:31.670 --> 00:09:36.140
But they are not formal
institutional hurdles

00:09:36.140 --> 00:09:38.650
that's anywhere like what you
have in the Catholic church.

00:09:38.650 --> 00:09:40.994
So what I end up doing
was finding every resource

00:09:40.994 --> 00:09:42.410
that I could get
my hands on about

00:09:42.410 --> 00:09:43.979
the Bible and homosexuality.

00:09:43.979 --> 00:09:46.270
And there are two main types
of resources that I found.

00:09:46.270 --> 00:09:50.640
One were very
academic texts, that

00:09:50.640 --> 00:09:53.870
often had a lot of
wonderful research in them,

00:09:53.870 --> 00:09:58.116
but were just quite
inaccessible for somebody who--

00:09:58.116 --> 00:09:59.490
for your average
person at church

00:09:59.490 --> 00:10:02.060
you might want to
ask to reconsider,

00:10:02.060 --> 00:10:03.900
who has a job and four kids.

00:10:03.900 --> 00:10:05.890
You can't say, go
read this 500 page

00:10:05.890 --> 00:10:09.020
tome that is in six languages.

00:10:09.020 --> 00:10:11.760
And then, could you let me
know what you think about it?

00:10:11.760 --> 00:10:13.780
That's not sufficient.

00:10:13.780 --> 00:10:15.740
But there's a lot of
important things there.

00:10:15.740 --> 00:10:18.740
But I also found a lot of
more popular level literature

00:10:18.740 --> 00:10:22.250
that was easy to read but do not
speak to people like my parents

00:10:22.250 --> 00:10:23.894
in a way that was
going to be helpful.

00:10:23.894 --> 00:10:25.310
Because it would
start off, and it

00:10:25.310 --> 00:10:27.672
would express presuppositions
about the Bible

00:10:27.672 --> 00:10:29.130
from the very
beginning, that would

00:10:29.130 --> 00:10:31.490
be offensive to, say, my dad.

00:10:31.490 --> 00:10:33.130
If you start off
and you say, well,

00:10:33.130 --> 00:10:35.420
the Bible says a
lot of wacky things

00:10:35.420 --> 00:10:38.584
and we just need to take it
a little bit less seriously,

00:10:38.584 --> 00:10:41.000
or if that's the impression
somebody gets in the first two

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:42.990
pages of your book, my dad
won't read beyond the first two

00:10:42.990 --> 00:10:44.200
pages of your book.

00:10:44.200 --> 00:10:46.000
Because the way
that this debate has

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.780
been cast for a lot of
conservative Christians,

00:10:48.780 --> 00:10:52.160
and part of the reason why
LGBT issues remain so fraught

00:10:52.160 --> 00:10:55.010
in a lot of the country--
especially Middle America

00:10:55.010 --> 00:10:57.840
and the South-- is
because many Christians

00:10:57.840 --> 00:11:02.170
have come to believe that if
they change what they think

00:11:02.170 --> 00:11:04.620
about same sex relationships,
they're actually

00:11:04.620 --> 00:11:08.040
going to be required to change
the entire infrastructure

00:11:08.040 --> 00:11:08.977
for their faith.

00:11:08.977 --> 00:11:10.810
And it's not just a
question of interpreting

00:11:10.810 --> 00:11:12.819
a select amount of
texts in the Bible,

00:11:12.819 --> 00:11:14.360
but it's a question
of whether or not

00:11:14.360 --> 00:11:17.330
the Bible should carry the
same weight and significance

00:11:17.330 --> 00:11:19.270
in their lives at all.

00:11:19.270 --> 00:11:21.640
And so, if I were to give
a resource to somebody

00:11:21.640 --> 00:11:24.170
at my church that
basically indicates, change

00:11:24.170 --> 00:11:26.200
your mind on same-sex
relationships

00:11:26.200 --> 00:11:29.170
by taking by Bible
less seriously,

00:11:29.170 --> 00:11:30.724
that's just not going to fly.

00:11:30.724 --> 00:11:32.640
Because you're going to
the very heart of what

00:11:32.640 --> 00:11:35.370
is most important to
someone's worldview

00:11:35.370 --> 00:11:38.210
and asking them to set it aside.

00:11:38.210 --> 00:11:42.050
Some people may be willing
to do that-- not most people.

00:11:42.050 --> 00:11:45.180
And if that is all that
LGBT kids growing up

00:11:45.180 --> 00:11:48.400
in conservative Christian
homes have at their disposal,

00:11:48.400 --> 00:11:52.332
when they're coming out, that's
not nearly sufficient for them.

00:11:52.332 --> 00:11:53.790
And so, part of
what I wanted to do

00:11:53.790 --> 00:11:58.550
was to take a lot of-- to
synthesize a lot of the best

00:11:58.550 --> 00:12:01.390
insights of academics
and biblical scholars,

00:12:01.390 --> 00:12:06.120
but then re-present them in both
a much more accessible form,

00:12:06.120 --> 00:12:09.820
but also, specifically, within
the theological framework

00:12:09.820 --> 00:12:11.960
that I grew up with.

00:12:11.960 --> 00:12:14.820
So sometimes that
requires revisions.

00:12:14.820 --> 00:12:18.564
There might be somebody-- you
can have some of the-- I mean,

00:12:18.564 --> 00:12:20.230
there are scholars I
cite in my book who

00:12:20.230 --> 00:12:25.384
are very progressive Christians,
who are atheists, agnostics.

00:12:25.384 --> 00:12:27.050
It doesn't really
matter what your faith

00:12:27.050 --> 00:12:31.520
is in terms of how you
do historiography, right.

00:12:31.520 --> 00:12:35.780
So one of the best
historians of ancient,

00:12:35.780 --> 00:12:37.780
what we would call,
sexuality-- even though it's

00:12:37.780 --> 00:12:40.560
kind of anachronism--
is David Halpern, who's

00:12:40.560 --> 00:12:42.400
not of any religion at all.

00:12:42.400 --> 00:12:44.730
But I would still happily
rely on a lot of this work

00:12:44.730 --> 00:12:48.630
to understand a lot of the
ancient constructs and contexts

00:12:48.630 --> 00:12:49.690
around sexuality.

00:12:49.690 --> 00:12:54.240
However, you can only rely
on that kind of work so far.

00:12:54.240 --> 00:12:56.630
And then you have to put
it within your own context

00:12:56.630 --> 00:12:59.710
and make sure that you're
grounding it within principles

00:12:59.710 --> 00:13:02.460
around scripture that
are consistent with those

00:13:02.460 --> 00:13:03.510
of your community.

00:13:03.510 --> 00:13:06.234
So that was really what I
set out to do with my dad,

00:13:06.234 --> 00:13:08.650
initially just, like, over
dinner table conversations when

00:13:08.650 --> 00:13:09.700
I was home.

00:13:09.700 --> 00:13:13.480
Then, it turned into engaging
our church much more widely.

00:13:13.480 --> 00:13:16.380
Then, it led me to,
two years later,

00:13:16.380 --> 00:13:20.370
give an hour-long talk at a
church in Wichita, Kansas,

00:13:20.370 --> 00:13:22.420
where I'm from,
all about the Bible

00:13:22.420 --> 00:13:26.570
and homosexuality, specifically
within that framework for more

00:13:26.570 --> 00:13:27.600
conservative Christians.

00:13:27.600 --> 00:13:30.900
And then that talk led to
the book, "God and the Gay

00:13:30.900 --> 00:13:32.830
Christian," which
came out last year.

00:13:32.830 --> 00:13:34.640
And so, all of it
is really designed.

00:13:34.640 --> 00:13:36.990
It's about giving
the specific language

00:13:36.990 --> 00:13:40.200
and the specific approach
that can be persuasive

00:13:40.200 --> 00:13:43.380
to evangelicals and to
conservative Christians.

00:13:43.380 --> 00:13:47.390
Some people are not open to
being persuaded right now.

00:13:47.390 --> 00:13:49.660
However, they're really
not my target audience.

00:13:49.660 --> 00:13:52.440
Because there are people--
they're still a minority--

00:13:52.440 --> 00:13:54.030
but there is a
significant minority

00:13:54.030 --> 00:13:58.430
of people in the evangelical
Christian world who

00:13:58.430 --> 00:13:59.822
are open to being persuaded.

00:13:59.822 --> 00:14:00.530
JACK MCCLURE: OK.

00:14:00.530 --> 00:14:01.290
MATTHEW VINES: And
you simply have

00:14:01.290 --> 00:14:03.970
to give them a strong enough
biblical argument in order

00:14:03.970 --> 00:14:04.960
to succeed.

00:14:04.960 --> 00:14:05.730
JACK MCCLURE: I think
one of the things

00:14:05.730 --> 00:14:07.938
that I noted in your book,
that I really appreciated,

00:14:07.938 --> 00:14:09.530
is how you bring it
to the experience.

00:14:09.530 --> 00:14:13.610
How you let the lived
experience of what's happening

00:14:13.610 --> 00:14:18.280
is what is happening within the
world of LGBT and transgendered

00:14:18.280 --> 00:14:21.300
and gay-- the whole
population-- I

00:14:21.300 --> 00:14:24.770
think you give good examples
of how they have experienced

00:14:24.770 --> 00:14:25.810
that separation.

00:14:25.810 --> 00:14:27.919
And I think you
addressed that, too.

00:14:27.919 --> 00:14:28.710
MATTHEW VINES: Yes.

00:14:28.710 --> 00:14:30.251
There are a couple
things about that.

00:14:30.251 --> 00:14:31.940
I think that experience
matters a lot.

00:14:31.940 --> 00:14:32.980
But especially
when you're talking

00:14:32.980 --> 00:14:34.930
to conservative
Christians, it's important

00:14:34.930 --> 00:14:37.720
that you don't present
experience as somehow

00:14:37.720 --> 00:14:40.100
overriding scripture.

00:14:40.100 --> 00:14:44.800
Because we all
know that there are

00:14:44.800 --> 00:14:50.090
a lot of really heart rending
stories that LGBT people have,

00:14:50.090 --> 00:14:55.710
about how they've been
treated by families, churches,

00:14:55.710 --> 00:14:57.390
society at large.

00:14:57.390 --> 00:15:00.830
However, a lot of
conservative Christians

00:15:00.830 --> 00:15:03.350
have a kind of
built-in resistance

00:15:03.350 --> 00:15:06.820
to listening to those stories,
when the stories are presented

00:15:06.820 --> 00:15:10.360
in opposition to scripture,
even if not explicitly.

00:15:10.360 --> 00:15:13.540
Part the reason why many
conservative Christians,

00:15:13.540 --> 00:15:17.640
you might send them,
like, if you have friends

00:15:17.640 --> 00:15:22.920
who are evangelical or just
on the more-- who are not,

00:15:22.920 --> 00:15:25.840
what I would call, are
not LGBT affirming.

00:15:25.840 --> 00:15:27.530
And then you might
send them a really

00:15:27.530 --> 00:15:30.060
heartwarming "It
gets better" video.

00:15:30.060 --> 00:15:31.830
And then they watch
it, and it really

00:15:31.830 --> 00:15:33.510
doesn't seem to
have reached them.

00:15:33.510 --> 00:15:34.470
It doesn't seem to
have engaged them.

00:15:34.470 --> 00:15:36.511
One reason why it doesn't
reach them, many times,

00:15:36.511 --> 00:15:41.964
is because there is this kind of
wall built up that they filter

00:15:41.964 --> 00:15:43.005
things like that through.

00:15:43.005 --> 00:15:47.230
And that wall is this biblical
interpretation that says,

00:15:47.230 --> 00:15:51.840
this experience, in order for
me to accept its legitimacy

00:15:51.840 --> 00:15:55.540
in a meaningful enough way to
make you rethink what I think,

00:15:55.540 --> 00:15:58.850
is in conflict with this core
aspect of my world-view, which

00:15:58.850 --> 00:15:59.830
is the Bible.

00:15:59.830 --> 00:16:02.685
And so, what I'm trying to do,
when I talk about experience,

00:16:02.685 --> 00:16:04.570
is specifically
talk about why it

00:16:04.570 --> 00:16:06.432
doesn't have to be in conflict.

00:16:06.432 --> 00:16:08.140
And so, at the very
beginning of my book,

00:16:08.140 --> 00:16:10.340
I talk about how, in
a sermon on the mount,

00:16:10.340 --> 00:16:16.150
in the book of Matthew,
Jesus offers his followers

00:16:16.150 --> 00:16:19.430
a kind of test for how to
discern false prophets.

00:16:19.430 --> 00:16:21.970
And he says, by their fruits
you will recognize them.

00:16:21.970 --> 00:16:26.150
A good tree bears good fruit,
and a bad tree bears bad fruit.

00:16:26.150 --> 00:16:28.130
And a good tree
cannot bear bad fruit,

00:16:28.130 --> 00:16:30.430
and a bad tree cannot
bear good fruit.

00:16:30.430 --> 00:16:33.490
And the Bible talks about
what the fruit of the Spirit

00:16:33.490 --> 00:16:35.530
looks like, in the
book of Galatians.

00:16:35.530 --> 00:16:39.730
So love, joy, peace,
patience, kindness, goodness,

00:16:39.730 --> 00:16:41.770
faithfulness,
gentleness, self-control,

00:16:41.770 --> 00:16:44.610
those kinds of things,
those are the types

00:16:44.610 --> 00:16:49.780
of traits that we see in many
same-sex relationships, today.

00:16:49.780 --> 00:16:54.470
Conversely, when LGBT people
are rejected by their churches,

00:16:54.470 --> 00:16:57.680
by their families,
that doesn't lead

00:16:57.680 --> 00:17:00.410
to the fruit of the Spirit,
as the Bible describes it.

00:17:00.410 --> 00:17:04.780
It leads to profound
devastation, isolation, harm,

00:17:04.780 --> 00:17:06.890
pain, suffering.

00:17:06.890 --> 00:17:09.349
And so that is kind
of a better way,

00:17:09.349 --> 00:17:11.750
I've found, to approach
the experience argument,

00:17:11.750 --> 00:17:14.849
is to put it in the context
of Jesus' own teachings.

00:17:14.849 --> 00:17:17.810
And say, according to
Jesus' own teachings,

00:17:17.810 --> 00:17:21.400
if we're seeing bad fruit, then
that's coming from a bad tree.

00:17:21.400 --> 00:17:25.380
And so, if the teaching that all
same-sex relationships are sin

00:17:25.380 --> 00:17:28.069
is producing bad
fruit, the teaching

00:17:28.069 --> 00:17:31.150
itself may be a bad tree.

00:17:31.150 --> 00:17:34.200
And so, that doesn't mean
that alone solves the issue,

00:17:34.200 --> 00:17:37.060
but it helps to open
the door for people

00:17:37.060 --> 00:17:39.720
to maybe be more
willing to reconsider.

00:17:39.720 --> 00:17:43.370
But then you still
have to convince them

00:17:43.370 --> 00:17:45.370
of how to read the main
biblical texts that

00:17:45.370 --> 00:17:47.630
refer to same-sex relations.

00:17:47.630 --> 00:17:48.530
That's doubtful.

00:17:48.530 --> 00:17:50.905
JACK MCCLURE: And isn't that
what your father showed you,

00:17:50.905 --> 00:17:52.070
in his experience?

00:17:52.070 --> 00:17:55.680
You came home-- in the telling
the story-- you came home,

00:17:55.680 --> 00:17:57.690
and it upset both
of them, the way

00:17:57.690 --> 00:17:59.240
you explained it in your book.

00:17:59.240 --> 00:18:03.020
But in the final
analysis, they loved you.

00:18:03.020 --> 00:18:05.620
And in their experience,
that changed--

00:18:05.620 --> 00:18:07.960
that had to change
their perspective on,

00:18:07.960 --> 00:18:10.020
what does it mean
to have a gay son?

00:18:10.020 --> 00:18:11.750
What does it mean to
have that member be

00:18:11.750 --> 00:18:13.646
in my family, and he's mine?

00:18:13.646 --> 00:18:14.520
MATTHEW VINES: Right.

00:18:14.520 --> 00:18:16.103
Well, they didn't
have any perspective

00:18:16.103 --> 00:18:18.650
on having a gay son before,
because that wasn't within what

00:18:18.650 --> 00:18:19.733
they thought was possible.

00:18:19.733 --> 00:18:22.590
But for my dad, I would say
that me coming out to him

00:18:22.590 --> 00:18:25.340
changed his heart.

00:18:25.340 --> 00:18:29.410
But his mind did not
change until we did

00:18:29.410 --> 00:18:30.890
an in-depth study of scripture.

00:18:30.890 --> 00:18:32.348
JACK MCCLURE: And
he would not have

00:18:32.348 --> 00:18:34.990
been open to that investigation
without that experience.

00:18:34.990 --> 00:18:35.870
MATTHEW VINES: Right.

00:18:35.870 --> 00:18:37.660
And so, experience
is very important.

00:18:37.660 --> 00:18:40.534
But also, rarely
is it sufficient--

00:18:40.534 --> 00:18:41.450
JACK MCCLURE: Exactly.

00:18:41.450 --> 00:18:42.210
MATTHEW VINES:
--for people coming

00:18:42.210 --> 00:18:43.919
from more conservative
faith backgrounds.

00:18:43.919 --> 00:18:45.376
JACK MCCLURE: And
I think that what

00:18:45.376 --> 00:18:47.910
we have in our population,
that's here with us today is,

00:18:47.910 --> 00:18:51.550
a deeper understanding, a better
understanding of how people

00:18:51.550 --> 00:18:58.020
are people, different as we are,
variances are more-- we talked

00:18:58.020 --> 00:19:01.110
at lunch, people from
all over, when you start

00:19:01.110 --> 00:19:03.370
bringing different
perspectives and views,

00:19:03.370 --> 00:19:04.980
changes the experience.

00:19:04.980 --> 00:19:06.850
And as you have
friends who are gay,

00:19:06.850 --> 00:19:09.547
and as you have family members
that are gay and lesbian,

00:19:09.547 --> 00:19:11.005
and all of that,
I think, then, you

00:19:11.005 --> 00:19:12.720
would take a different approach.

00:19:12.720 --> 00:19:16.670
Your research is really timely,
in terms of the conversation

00:19:16.670 --> 00:19:17.570
that's happening.

00:19:17.570 --> 00:19:20.090
Because you went
under it from not just

00:19:20.090 --> 00:19:21.980
an academic point
of view, but it

00:19:21.980 --> 00:19:23.700
seems to me that you
tried to also look

00:19:23.700 --> 00:19:26.090
at the culture behind
it, in addition

00:19:26.090 --> 00:19:28.660
to just a literal academic
part-- which, of culture, is

00:19:28.660 --> 00:19:30.170
extremely important.

00:19:30.170 --> 00:19:33.010
Would you share a
little bit about how

00:19:33.010 --> 00:19:35.576
that formed your thinking?

00:19:35.576 --> 00:19:37.200
MATTHEW VINES: Well,
part of-- and this

00:19:37.200 --> 00:19:39.241
may not be the exact
question that you're asking.

00:19:39.241 --> 00:19:41.170
So tell me if I'm
going off-track, here.

00:19:41.170 --> 00:19:45.160
But part of the cultural
analysis, for me,

00:19:45.160 --> 00:19:50.950
is about how to take a message
and really put it into action.

00:19:50.950 --> 00:19:53.830
So how do you actually get
into-- if it is possible,

00:19:53.830 --> 00:19:56.810
and I do think it is
possible-- so my dad, right,

00:19:56.810 --> 00:19:59.890
it's kind of like what I was
seeking to fashion was, like,

00:19:59.890 --> 00:20:04.380
almost a key to unlock the
door to changing his mind.

00:20:04.380 --> 00:20:06.670
And relationships are a
critical piece of that.

00:20:06.670 --> 00:20:10.390
But the scriptural argument
is equally critical.

00:20:10.390 --> 00:20:13.310
And so, it's like the book
is the scriptural argument.

00:20:13.310 --> 00:20:16.600
But then the question is,
from a cultural standpoint,

00:20:16.600 --> 00:20:18.910
even once you have that,
there's still the question of,

00:20:18.910 --> 00:20:20.680
how do you actually
put that into practice

00:20:20.680 --> 00:20:23.037
to affect widespread change?

00:20:23.037 --> 00:20:24.620
And so, that's really
what I'm seeking

00:20:24.620 --> 00:20:27.070
to do through the nonprofit
organization that I run.

00:20:27.070 --> 00:20:28.570
JACK MCCLURE: And
the name of it is?

00:20:28.570 --> 00:20:29.710
MATTHEW VINES: It's called
the Reaffirmation Project,

00:20:29.710 --> 00:20:31.940
and I started it a
couple years ago.

00:20:31.940 --> 00:20:35.740
We run conferences around
the country for Christians,

00:20:35.740 --> 00:20:38.470
what we call LGBT
affirming Christians

00:20:38.470 --> 00:20:40.950
in non-affirming contexts.

00:20:40.950 --> 00:20:43.110
And it's specifically
designed to give them

00:20:43.110 --> 00:20:45.470
the Bible based
tools that they need

00:20:45.470 --> 00:20:48.280
to empower them to
become vocal advocates

00:20:48.280 --> 00:20:51.290
for the LGBT community
in their churches.

00:20:51.290 --> 00:20:53.960
So we just did a big conference
in Atlanta, a week and a half

00:20:53.960 --> 00:20:54.580
ago.

00:20:54.580 --> 00:20:56.640
We had several hundred
people come from mostly

00:20:56.640 --> 00:20:57.817
across the South.

00:20:57.817 --> 00:20:59.400
And the goal through
these conferences

00:20:59.400 --> 00:21:01.460
is about training and equipping.

00:21:01.460 --> 00:21:04.240
So because there are what I
call "silent sympathizers,"

00:21:04.240 --> 00:21:07.720
in churches of almost all kinds,
no matter how conservative,

00:21:07.720 --> 00:21:10.590
a minority people who
feel the sense of conflict

00:21:10.590 --> 00:21:12.050
about their church's posture.

00:21:12.050 --> 00:21:13.990
But the main reason
why they don't so

00:21:13.990 --> 00:21:17.307
give voice to their sense
of internal conflict

00:21:17.307 --> 00:21:18.890
is because they don't
know how to talk

00:21:18.890 --> 00:21:21.240
about the Bible and
same-sex relationships

00:21:21.240 --> 00:21:22.710
in a way that will
even potentially

00:21:22.710 --> 00:21:24.930
be persuasive to other
people in their church.

00:21:24.930 --> 00:21:27.130
And so, what we worked
to do is to identify

00:21:27.130 --> 00:21:29.910
those silent sympathizers,
and then to equip them,

00:21:29.910 --> 00:21:32.430
to give them the
messages that they need.

00:21:32.430 --> 00:21:34.020
And it doesn't make it easy.

00:21:34.020 --> 00:21:35.920
It doesn't make
them-- that does not

00:21:35.920 --> 00:21:37.436
produce success with everyone.

00:21:37.436 --> 00:21:38.810
It probably only
produces success

00:21:38.810 --> 00:21:40.020
in a minority of people.

00:21:40.020 --> 00:21:41.390
But really, that's all you need.

00:21:41.390 --> 00:21:43.556
Because in a church, like
the one that I grew up in,

00:21:43.556 --> 00:21:47.010
of 2,000 people, not a single
person, before I came out,

00:21:47.010 --> 00:21:50.010
had been willing to say
publicly that they did not

00:21:50.010 --> 00:21:52.822
believe that same-sex
relationships were sinful.

00:21:52.822 --> 00:21:55.280
And once I came out, we found
out that some of our friends,

00:21:55.280 --> 00:21:58.030
privately, did not believe
that same-sex relationships are

00:21:58.030 --> 00:21:58.932
wrong.

00:21:58.932 --> 00:22:00.890
But they would not give
voice to that publicly,

00:22:00.890 --> 00:22:05.680
because the pressure not
to do so was so great,

00:22:05.680 --> 00:22:08.490
and they didn't know how to
really speak to people's core

00:22:08.490 --> 00:22:10.100
concerns about that.

00:22:10.100 --> 00:22:12.730
So that's really our goal,
then, through the Reformation

00:22:12.730 --> 00:22:13.660
Project.

00:22:13.660 --> 00:22:14.460
We know we have--

00:22:14.460 --> 00:22:16.710
JACK MCCLURE: It seems like
it's an opportunity, then,

00:22:16.710 --> 00:22:18.910
for people to give voice
to their own thoughts

00:22:18.910 --> 00:22:20.640
and their own experiences.

00:22:20.640 --> 00:22:24.290
So that's a very important part
of unloosing, understanding,

00:22:24.290 --> 00:22:27.140
I think, about their difference.

00:22:27.140 --> 00:22:29.800
I think we're seeing
that in religions,

00:22:29.800 --> 00:22:32.660
certainly from a Roman
Catholic point of view.

00:22:32.660 --> 00:22:34.142
I am very interested
in how we're

00:22:34.142 --> 00:22:36.600
going to interface with our
Protestant brothers and sisters

00:22:36.600 --> 00:22:40.130
to finally become unified.

00:22:40.130 --> 00:22:42.050
The research that
you did, and the part

00:22:42.050 --> 00:22:44.580
that I found so interesting
and intriguing with what

00:22:44.580 --> 00:22:46.494
you were looking at
is, you not only looked

00:22:46.494 --> 00:22:47.660
at the culture of that time.

00:22:47.660 --> 00:22:50.150
Now, you're trying to bring it
to the culture at this time.

00:22:50.150 --> 00:22:51.650
I thought that was significant.

00:22:51.650 --> 00:22:55.580
You gave an example of how
some things have been forbidden

00:22:55.580 --> 00:22:58.610
