not, in our understanding,

00:22:58.610 --> 00:22:59.530
today.

00:22:59.530 --> 00:23:01.660
Would that help any
clarity, bring clarity,

00:23:01.660 --> 00:23:04.800
do you think, to the people
about how texts can be used?

00:23:04.800 --> 00:23:07.300
I think it's important for them
to understand that from you.

00:23:07.300 --> 00:23:08.300
MATTHEW VINES: OK, yeah.

00:23:08.300 --> 00:23:10.820
So part of the cultural
argument that I make,

00:23:10.820 --> 00:23:15.450
in terms of interpreting texts,
specifically ancient texts,

00:23:15.450 --> 00:23:20.190
requires a broader understanding
of ancient concepts

00:23:20.190 --> 00:23:24.840
and constructions of
what we call sexuality.

00:23:24.840 --> 00:23:26.990
JACK MCCLURE: Or any kind
of given communication.

00:23:26.990 --> 00:23:30.400
For instance-- and this will
be really strange-- but today,

00:23:30.400 --> 00:23:32.570
it's hard for us not
to imagine people

00:23:32.570 --> 00:23:34.410
being able to read and write.

00:23:34.410 --> 00:23:36.680
And having access
to pencil and paper,

00:23:36.680 --> 00:23:40.100
with the computerization that
we have, it's almost instant.

00:23:40.100 --> 00:23:43.120
But when we look back,
