00:23:43.120 --> 00:23:47.060
they relied on auditory, and
listening, and telling stories.

00:23:47.060 --> 00:23:49.880
And how those stories then
became part of scripture.

00:23:49.880 --> 00:23:51.810
And what caused that.

00:23:51.810 --> 00:23:54.790
I thought that the way you
presented your information

00:23:54.790 --> 00:23:56.950
about that was very telling.

00:23:56.950 --> 00:23:59.570
Because it opened up
that something that

00:23:59.570 --> 00:24:04.180
was extremely important to be
taboo with them at that time

00:24:04.180 --> 00:24:07.980
was hygiene related perhaps,
or related other things.

00:24:07.980 --> 00:24:10.160
And we don't see
it that way today.

00:24:10.160 --> 00:24:13.160
We see difference, we see
a different understanding.

00:24:13.160 --> 00:24:15.350
You presented those
kind of understandings,

00:24:15.350 --> 00:24:19.366
for me, when you reinterpreted--
not reinterpreted.

00:24:19.366 --> 00:24:20.740
What's the language
that you use?

00:24:20.740 --> 00:24:22.024
You re-con-- the text.

00:24:22.024 --> 00:24:23.690
MATTHEW VINES: Well,
I mean, I certainly

00:24:23.690 --> 00:24:25.390
am arguing for a
reinterpretation.

00:24:25.390 --> 00:24:30.740
But I wouldn't place that
agency primarily on me.

00:24:30.740 --> 00:24:32.750
Because part of my
goal with the book

00:24:32.750 --> 00:24:36.210
was not actually to be making
any original arguments,

00:24:36.210 --> 00:24:37.700
as odd as that may sound.

00:24:37.700 --> 00:24:42.340
Because what I'm trying to do is
to synthesize and to popularize

00:24:42.340 --> 00:24:45.780
the best of the arguments
and insights that

00:24:45.780 --> 00:24:50.180
have been pioneered,
debated, vetted, and refined

00:24:50.180 --> 00:24:52.630
by people with far
greater expertise

00:24:52.630 --> 00:24:55.536
in a lot of particular fields
than I could possibly have.

00:24:55.536 --> 00:24:57.410
JACK MCCLURE: You looked
very widely, though.

00:24:57.410 --> 00:24:58.320
MATTHEW VINES: Very widely.

00:24:58.320 --> 00:24:58.730
JACK MCCLURE: Yes.

00:24:58.730 --> 00:25:00.563
MATTHEW VINES: And so
that's why my goal is,

00:25:00.563 --> 00:25:02.000
I didn't want to--
if I was going

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:04.480
to be making an argument that
actually hadn't been made

00:25:04.480 --> 00:25:09.600
and challenged and then
supported again and further

00:25:09.600 --> 00:25:11.730
refined, I didn't want
to make that argument,

00:25:11.730 --> 00:25:14.270
because that argument would
be likely to fall apart.

00:25:14.270 --> 00:25:15.890
So with all the
arguments that I make

00:25:15.890 --> 00:25:20.690
and all the historical
analyses, interpretations,

00:25:20.690 --> 00:25:23.110
I don't want any of them
to be original to me.

00:25:23.110 --> 00:25:25.950
So in that sense, like, I am
arguing for a reinterpretation.

00:25:25.950 --> 00:25:28.640
But I'm also wanting
to argue-- I'm also

00:25:28.640 --> 00:25:31.760
wanting to point people toward
the scholars, and the writers,

00:25:31.760 --> 00:25:33.810
and theologians who
I think have maybe

00:25:33.810 --> 00:25:37.820
done the best work on this
particular nook, right,

00:25:37.820 --> 00:25:41.436
in this particular cranny,
all these particular aspects.

00:25:41.436 --> 00:25:42.810
And then, bring
them all together

00:25:42.810 --> 00:25:44.654
into a more cohesive whole.

00:25:44.654 --> 00:25:46.570
JACK MCCLURE: Was it
evident to you, somewhere

00:25:46.570 --> 00:25:48.930
along the line of your
research and your reading

00:25:48.930 --> 00:25:52.390
and looking and talking with
your dad and looking forward,

00:25:52.390 --> 00:25:57.220
did it become evident to you,
sometime, that you said aha,

00:25:57.220 --> 00:26:01.680
this is different than
what I had thought?

00:26:01.680 --> 00:26:03.300
How did that come to you?

00:26:03.300 --> 00:26:05.852
I would be very interested,
if you could pinpoint it.

00:26:05.852 --> 00:26:06.560
It might be hard.

00:26:06.560 --> 00:26:07.000
MATTHEW VINES: Yeah.

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:08.680
I mean, there are
a couple of things,

00:26:08.680 --> 00:26:11.480
and a couple of specific texts,
that I'm happy to go into.

00:26:11.480 --> 00:26:13.510
And then, if anybody
has questions

00:26:13.510 --> 00:26:15.854
we'd be happy to
take them that point.

00:26:15.854 --> 00:26:17.270
So think about it
if you have any.

00:26:17.270 --> 00:26:18.510
JACK MCCLURE: Yeah.

00:26:18.510 --> 00:26:21.090
MATTHEW VINES: So one
text is this famous text

00:26:21.090 --> 00:26:23.420
from the "Old Testament"
about the destruction of Sodom

00:26:23.420 --> 00:26:27.360
and Gomorrah, which is no
longer really at the forefront

00:26:27.360 --> 00:26:28.770
of the conversation anymore.

00:26:28.770 --> 00:26:31.010
But it's remarkable how
many Christians still

00:26:31.010 --> 00:26:35.370
associate Sodom and
Gomorrah with gayness.

00:26:35.370 --> 00:26:38.300
So, when I asked my
dad in high school

00:26:38.300 --> 00:26:40.300
why we were against
gay rights-- because I

00:26:40.300 --> 00:26:44.050
knew that we were, but I wasn't
really sure why-- he just

00:26:44.050 --> 00:26:47.430
sat me down, opened his
Bible to Genesis, Chapter 19,

00:26:47.430 --> 00:26:49.180
and read to me this
story where God

00:26:49.180 --> 00:26:53.080
sends two angels, in the form
of men, into the city of Sodom.

00:26:53.080 --> 00:26:57.390
The men of Sodom attempt or
threaten to rape the angels.

00:26:57.390 --> 00:27:00.715
And God then destroys the
city with fire and brimstone.

00:27:00.715 --> 00:27:02.840
And so, because these men
were threatening to rape,

00:27:02.840 --> 00:27:06.250
at least what appeared
to be, other men, my dad

00:27:06.250 --> 00:27:08.760
said, well, these men
wanted to have sex with men.

00:27:08.760 --> 00:27:10.110
God destroyed them for it.

00:27:10.110 --> 00:27:11.786
That's why we're
against gay rights.

00:27:11.786 --> 00:27:14.160
That does not make my dad
sound like a very sophisticated

00:27:14.160 --> 00:27:15.160
person.

00:27:15.160 --> 00:27:17.010
But in fact, he really is.

00:27:17.010 --> 00:27:20.790
He just wasn't on this
topic, because he didn't

00:27:20.790 --> 00:27:22.120
know any openly gay people.

00:27:22.120 --> 00:27:25.050
He had never been forced to
think very deeply about it.

00:27:25.050 --> 00:27:29.480
But when I came out to him, that
was the first text that he went

00:27:29.480 --> 00:27:32.320
back to, and he
sort of said, hm, I

00:27:32.320 --> 00:27:35.410
may not as much as I thought
I knew about this subject.

00:27:35.410 --> 00:27:38.160
Because this text,
now, looking at it

00:27:38.160 --> 00:27:44.340
in the light of a broader
understanding of gay people,

00:27:44.340 --> 00:27:46.480
that is so different from
the type of relationship

00:27:46.480 --> 00:27:48.339
that you, Matthew, want, right?

00:27:48.339 --> 00:27:50.380
Like, we're talking about
a threatened gang rape.

00:27:50.380 --> 00:27:50.640
JACK MCCLURE: Mhm.

00:27:50.640 --> 00:27:53.400
MATTHEW VINES: And for anybody
who knows any gay people,

00:27:53.400 --> 00:27:56.280
these distinctions are
incredibly obvious.

00:27:56.280 --> 00:27:59.350
But if you don't know any gay
people, and you just know,

00:27:59.350 --> 00:28:00.870
well, I know
homosexuality is a sin.

00:28:00.870 --> 00:28:02.345
I know that's because
of stuff in the Bible.

00:28:02.345 --> 00:28:03.720
I know people
bring up this text,

00:28:03.720 --> 00:28:04.940
so there must be connection.

00:28:04.940 --> 00:28:06.860
Then you go into the text
searching for the connection.

00:28:06.860 --> 00:28:08.510
And even though
it's quite tenuous,

00:28:08.510 --> 00:28:09.926
you don't worry
about it too much.

00:28:09.926 --> 00:28:12.440
Because that's just the
way it's supposed to be.

00:28:12.440 --> 00:28:16.000
So for my dad, recognizing
that that text was

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:17.330
about a very different thing.

00:28:17.330 --> 00:28:19.830
And then also-- and as I go
into much more depth in the book

00:28:19.830 --> 00:28:22.070
about the history of
interpretation of the Sodom

00:28:22.070 --> 00:28:24.010
story, how for
the first, really,

00:28:24.010 --> 00:28:26.500
2,000 years of that story's
existence-- of course,

00:28:26.500 --> 00:28:28.530
it dates back probably
to about 1400 BC,

00:28:28.530 --> 00:28:30.710
at least in the oral
tradition-- it was not

00:28:30.710 --> 00:28:34.390
understood by the Israelites
and the ancient Jews

00:28:34.390 --> 00:28:37.560
to be about same sex anything.

00:28:37.560 --> 00:28:40.290
And then the 20 other
references to Sodom and Gomorrah

00:28:40.290 --> 00:28:44.450
in the rest of the Bible do
not refer to same-sex behavior

00:28:44.450 --> 00:28:46.480
as part of the sin
of Sodom, but are

00:28:46.480 --> 00:28:48.390
quite explicit that
the sin of Sodom

00:28:48.390 --> 00:28:50.140
has to do with
arrogance and apathy

00:28:50.140 --> 00:28:53.547
toward the poor,
oppression, inhospitality,

00:28:53.547 --> 00:28:54.630
all sorts of those things.

00:28:54.630 --> 00:28:58.740
So for my dad, that really
was a door opener for him

00:28:58.740 --> 00:29:00.552
in going back to some
of these other texts.

00:29:00.552 --> 00:29:02.010
Because he figured,
if I could have

00:29:02.010 --> 00:29:05.660
been mistaken about
this text, then it's

00:29:05.660 --> 00:29:08.190
possible I've been mistaken
about the other texts.

00:29:08.190 --> 00:29:10.120
And there's another
really important text

00:29:10.120 --> 00:29:12.850
in the "New Testament,"
by the Apostle Paul,

00:29:12.850 --> 00:29:19.240
in Romans Chapter I, where
Paul describes and condemns

00:29:19.240 --> 00:29:21.140
lustful, same-sex behavior.

00:29:21.140 --> 00:29:24.510
He talks about how-- without
going into all the detail--

00:29:24.510 --> 00:29:27.170
he talks about how
women exchanged natural

00:29:27.170 --> 00:29:31.160
for unnatural relations, and
men abandoned natural relations

00:29:31.160 --> 00:29:33.540
with women, became inflamed
with lust, one for another,

00:29:33.540 --> 00:29:36.120
and committed indecent
acts with other men.

00:29:36.120 --> 00:29:38.320
And I remember
just sitting down.

00:29:38.320 --> 00:29:40.800
For a lot of
evangelicals, that text

00:29:40.800 --> 00:29:43.730
is perhaps the
most important one,

00:29:43.730 --> 00:29:47.550
in terms of what would be
a stumbling block for them

00:29:47.550 --> 00:29:48.485
for reconsidering.

00:29:48.485 --> 00:29:49.860
I just remember
telling my dad, I

00:29:49.860 --> 00:29:54.100
was like, Dad-- like, over
our dinner table one night--

00:29:54.100 --> 00:29:57.299
like, these people are
consumed with their lusts.

00:29:57.299 --> 00:29:59.090
It specifically is
talking about people who

00:29:59.090 --> 00:30:01.150
are just, like, lust-filled.

00:30:01.150 --> 00:30:05.100
And I was like, that is
not my goal or my vision

00:30:05.100 --> 00:30:06.070
for my future, right.

00:30:06.070 --> 00:30:08.040
Like, I want to have
a relationship that's

00:30:08.040 --> 00:30:10.970
like the relationship
you have with Mom, that's

00:30:10.970 --> 00:30:15.460
a stable, long-term
relationship with the basis

00:30:15.460 --> 00:30:19.050
of a home and a family.

00:30:19.050 --> 00:30:23.910
I was just, like, to me, these
are really different issues.

00:30:23.910 --> 00:30:27.089
And that text is a
very complicated text.

00:30:27.089 --> 00:30:29.130
So there's a lot more the
could be said about it.

00:30:29.130 --> 00:30:33.220
But for my dad, just recognizing
that distinction, you're right,

00:30:33.220 --> 00:30:34.070
he was saying.

00:30:34.070 --> 00:30:36.240
This is explicitly
talking about people who

00:30:36.240 --> 00:30:38.400
were consumed with lustfulness.

00:30:38.400 --> 00:30:41.050
And he just never
really considered

00:30:41.050 --> 00:30:43.770
that it's possible that there
are same-sex relationships that

00:30:43.770 --> 00:30:45.040
don't fit into that paradigm.

00:30:45.040 --> 00:30:45.940
JACK MCCLURE: Mhm.

00:30:45.940 --> 00:30:48.170
MATTHEW VINES: I know that
can sound very ignorant.

00:30:48.170 --> 00:30:52.120
I mean, in a sense,
because it is ignorant.

00:30:52.120 --> 00:30:54.220
But it's not
necessarily hateful.

00:30:54.220 --> 00:30:57.400
Like, a lot of people
assume that Christians

00:30:57.400 --> 00:30:59.650
who are against same-sex
marriage must be,

00:30:59.650 --> 00:31:02.860
like, terribly bigoted,
hateful people.

00:31:02.860 --> 00:31:04.600
And you can always
find some examples

00:31:04.600 --> 00:31:05.970
of truly hateful people.

00:31:05.970 --> 00:31:06.803
JACK MCCLURE: Right.

00:31:06.803 --> 00:31:08.900
MATTHEW VINES: But in the
main, that's not true.

00:31:08.900 --> 00:31:12.090
It's like, my dad never had
any malice toward anyone.

00:31:12.090 --> 00:31:13.646
It doesn't mean
that he was right.

00:31:13.646 --> 00:31:15.020
It doesn't mean
that his position

00:31:15.020 --> 00:31:18.120
was accurate or helpful.

00:31:18.120 --> 00:31:21.270
It's inaccurate and
does harm to people.

00:31:21.270 --> 00:31:25.345
But if you start with a posture
of anger toward the harm

00:31:25.345 --> 00:31:28.660
that people's beliefs do, then
you put them on the defensive.

00:31:28.660 --> 00:31:30.910
Because then they typically
feel like their characters

00:31:30.910 --> 00:31:32.200
being maligned.

00:31:32.200 --> 00:31:34.220
And so, I find it
much more helpful

00:31:34.220 --> 00:31:37.880
to start a posture
of relationship,

00:31:37.880 --> 00:31:41.120
of genuine affection or
respect for the person,

00:31:41.120 --> 00:31:42.920
especially if you know them.

00:31:42.920 --> 00:31:46.660
And respect for their
heart and their motives.

00:31:46.660 --> 00:31:48.270
But then, within
that context, really

00:31:48.270 --> 00:31:51.170
earnestly asking them
to look more critically

00:31:51.170 --> 00:31:52.720
at the consequences
of their beliefs.

00:31:52.720 --> 00:31:54.303
And say, even though
I know you're not

00:31:54.303 --> 00:31:56.790
coming from a place
of wanting to do harm,

00:31:56.790 --> 00:32:00.530
these beliefs, they still have
this harmful impact on my life.

00:32:00.530 --> 00:32:03.260
And so, would you be willing
to look at this a bit

00:32:03.260 --> 00:32:04.210
more closely with me?

00:32:04.210 --> 00:32:07.070
I found that to be vastly more
effective than an approach

00:32:07.070 --> 00:32:09.310
to just sort of
assumes that everybody

00:32:09.310 --> 00:32:12.050
who's against gay
marriage is hateful.

00:32:12.050 --> 00:32:16.430
It's much more effective not to
try to ascribe a single motive

00:32:16.430 --> 00:32:18.340
to a very wide group of people.

00:32:18.340 --> 00:32:21.950
But instead to meet
people on their own terms

00:32:21.950 --> 00:32:24.320
in the context of
relationship and community.

00:32:24.320 --> 00:32:29.120
And then focus on the impact,
rather than the intention.

00:32:29.120 --> 00:32:30.255
So that's sort of a--

00:32:30.255 --> 00:32:31.130
JACK MCCLURE: Thanks.

00:32:31.130 --> 00:32:32.260
MATTHEW VINES: Yeah.

