00:34:33.480 --> 00:34:35.710
So it is true that
the book of Leviticus

00:34:35.710 --> 00:34:39.590
prohibits male, same-sex sex.

00:34:39.590 --> 00:34:41.840
And of course, it also
prohibits a ton of other things

00:34:41.840 --> 00:34:44.520
that Christians
don't follow anymore.

00:34:44.520 --> 00:34:47.949
But that's not really
hypocrisy, because Christians

00:34:47.949 --> 00:34:49.993
who are being more
informed about it

00:34:49.993 --> 00:34:51.659
are not going to
ground their opposition

00:34:51.659 --> 00:34:54.000
to same-sex relationships
primarily in Leviticus

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:55.210
or in the "Old Testament."

00:34:55.210 --> 00:34:56.800
Because the "New
Testament" talks

00:34:56.800 --> 00:34:59.240
extensively about how Jesus
fulfilled the "Old Testament"

00:34:59.240 --> 00:35:00.030
law.

00:35:00.030 --> 00:35:01.680
And Jesus says, not
one jot or tittle

00:35:01.680 --> 00:35:03.140
will fall away from the law.

00:35:03.140 --> 00:35:05.510
But the way that the "New
Testament" authors interpret

00:35:05.510 --> 00:35:08.140
that is in the context
of the "Old Testament"

00:35:08.140 --> 00:35:10.490
law no longer
having force, longer

00:35:10.490 --> 00:35:14.380
applying to God's people,
under the New Covenant,

00:35:14.380 --> 00:35:17.160
in the same way that it did
to the ancient Israelites.

00:35:17.160 --> 00:35:20.500
So most Christians who are being
more thoughtful about it would

00:35:20.500 --> 00:35:23.930
ground their opposition to
same-sex relationships in "New

00:35:23.930 --> 00:35:28.220
Testament" texts that are
part of the New Covenant,

00:35:28.220 --> 00:35:29.910
or in sort of a
broader-- what they say

00:35:29.910 --> 00:35:32.740
is a broader narrative
arc, within scripture,

00:35:32.740 --> 00:35:35.810
from the Genesis
creation texts, then

00:35:35.810 --> 00:35:37.950
through to how the
"New Testament,"

00:35:37.950 --> 00:35:41.570
they believe, interprets
or uses those texts.

00:35:41.570 --> 00:35:44.420
So in that sense, yeah.

00:35:44.420 --> 00:35:47.680
Part of what I'm trying
to do is to persuade

00:35:47.680 --> 00:35:50.080
conservative Christians to
rethink their interpretation.

00:35:50.080 --> 00:35:51.680
Another part of what
I'm trying to do

00:35:51.680 --> 00:35:54.320
is to persuade more
progressive Christians

00:35:54.320 --> 00:35:56.670
to make better arguments
when they're in conversations

00:35:56.670 --> 00:35:58.080
with conservative Christians.

00:35:58.080 --> 00:36:00.980
And so, I don't think, if
your argument to somebody

00:36:00.980 --> 00:36:04.350
is, why are you
against gay marriage

00:36:04.350 --> 00:36:07.230
when you're not
against polyester?

00:36:07.230 --> 00:36:11.680
I've seen that argument persuade
people about 0% of the time.

00:36:11.680 --> 00:36:14.410
Because it doesn't
demonstrate an awareness

00:36:14.410 --> 00:36:17.390
of why they actually believe
what they believe, right.

00:36:17.390 --> 00:36:21.350
So you're kind of just
working around the edges.

00:36:21.350 --> 00:36:23.660
What's much more
interesting, though,

00:36:23.660 --> 00:36:25.800
is that same
principle-- it's not

00:36:25.800 --> 00:36:28.340
say that there is no
inconsistency in how things are

00:36:28.340 --> 00:36:30.339
being applied, but you
have to be really careful

00:36:30.339 --> 00:36:31.580
how you approach that.

00:36:31.580 --> 00:36:35.780
So, much more interesting
text than the polyester texts,

00:36:35.780 --> 00:36:37.830
or than any of the
prohibitions in Leviticus,

00:36:37.830 --> 00:36:45.030
is from 1 Corinthians, Chapter
11, Versus 14 and 15, where

00:36:45.030 --> 00:36:48.390
it specifically says, Do
you not know that nature

00:36:48.390 --> 00:36:51.150
itself teaches that for
a man to have long hair

00:36:51.150 --> 00:36:53.810
is a disgrace to him, but
for a woman to have long hair

00:36:53.810 --> 00:36:55.800
is to her glory?

00:36:55.800 --> 00:36:57.510
The reason why this
is so fascinating

00:36:57.510 --> 00:36:59.880
is because the text
of Romans 1, which

00:36:59.880 --> 00:37:01.420
is the longest "New
Testament" text,

00:37:01.420 --> 00:37:04.600
or longest biblical text
referring to same-sex behavior,

00:37:04.600 --> 00:37:07.190
uses two of the very
same Greek words-- words

00:37:07.190 --> 00:37:08.660
for nature and for disgrace.

00:37:08.660 --> 00:37:12.619
That's phusis and [? atomia. ?]
And in the Romans 1,

00:37:12.619 --> 00:37:14.160
a lot of conservative
Christians want

00:37:14.160 --> 00:37:17.460
to say that those words about
what goes against nature

00:37:17.460 --> 00:37:20.570
refer to what they call
the "creational order."

00:37:20.570 --> 00:37:22.300
Or something that
was established

00:37:22.300 --> 00:37:24.720
at the very beginning in
Genesis 1 and 2 and, therefore,

00:37:24.720 --> 00:37:28.630
something that is normative
for Christians today.

00:37:28.630 --> 00:37:32.066
But ask them how they
interpret 1 Corinthians 11,

00:37:32.066 --> 00:37:33.690
and most Christians
today will tell you

00:37:33.690 --> 00:37:35.740
that they think
nature in that text

00:37:35.740 --> 00:37:38.530
refers to social
custom or convention.

00:37:38.530 --> 00:37:40.300
And that what makes
it disgraceful

00:37:40.300 --> 00:37:44.450
has to do with what the given
cultural norms of the day are.

00:37:44.450 --> 00:37:47.570
And I happen to agree with
them in 1 Corinthians 11.

00:37:47.570 --> 00:37:49.630
The term "nature" has
a really wide range

00:37:49.630 --> 00:37:53.320
of potential uses
in ancient Greek,

00:37:53.320 --> 00:37:57.980
and in a lot of contemporaneous
texts, extra-biblical texts,

00:37:57.980 --> 00:38:00.696
and within the
biblical canon itself.

00:38:00.696 --> 00:38:02.320
What that means,
though, is, if they're

00:38:02.320 --> 00:38:05.890
willing to read those very same
terms in the "New Testament"

00:38:05.890 --> 00:38:09.850
in a way that is culturally
conditioned and confined,

00:38:09.850 --> 00:38:12.560
then that's a much better
text to use for saying, well,

00:38:12.560 --> 00:38:14.990
why didn't you read
Romans 1 the same way?

00:38:14.990 --> 00:38:18.330
Because it's actually
operating within the world

00:38:18.330 --> 00:38:19.610
that they're operating within.

00:38:19.610 --> 00:38:23.010
So it's much better to make
sure you know what they believe

00:38:23.010 --> 00:38:25.790
their strongest arguments to be,
or their most important texts

00:38:25.790 --> 00:38:27.340
to be going into it.

00:38:27.340 --> 00:38:29.780
And then focus on
texts and arguments

00:38:29.780 --> 00:38:31.550
that are relevant
to those things.

00:38:31.550 --> 00:38:33.010
So that's part of
what's actually

00:38:33.010 --> 00:38:36.680
made a lot of my conversations
really good and effective,

00:38:36.680 --> 00:38:39.450
is because a lot of
evangelicals have never

00:38:39.450 --> 00:38:42.460
been engaged on their own terms
in a really meaningful way

00:38:42.460 --> 00:38:44.400
before, on this topic.

00:38:44.400 --> 00:38:47.450
And so, all that they've ever--
the only sort of paradigm

00:38:47.450 --> 00:38:49.750
that they've had is
a combat paradigm

00:38:49.750 --> 00:38:51.820
of, like, the secular
LGBT activists

00:38:51.820 --> 00:38:55.740
versus the faithful
conservative Christians.

00:38:55.740 --> 00:38:58.660
And so, it's very easy,
then, to people-- for them

00:38:58.660 --> 00:39:01.140
to just sort of stay entrenched
in their belief system.

00:39:01.140 --> 00:39:02.125
And say, look, our
whole belief system

00:39:02.125 --> 00:39:03.583
is under attack by
people who think

00:39:03.583 --> 00:39:07.580
that the whole idea of God
and religion is stupid.

00:39:07.580 --> 00:39:09.290
And so, that way
it's much more of a,

00:39:09.290 --> 00:39:12.350
we're keeping our community,
we're keeping our identity

00:39:12.350 --> 00:39:14.840
and our values
intact and preserved.

00:39:14.840 --> 00:39:16.690
But the conversation
shifts radically

00:39:16.690 --> 00:39:20.170
when you actually have a
member of the community who

00:39:20.170 --> 00:39:22.840
shares all those
core beliefs, who

00:39:22.840 --> 00:39:25.990
cares about the community, who
has relationships with people

00:39:25.990 --> 00:39:28.360
in the community, who
is simply asking people

00:39:28.360 --> 00:39:29.900
to reconsider their
interpretation

00:39:29.900 --> 00:39:31.770
of a select amount of texts.

00:39:31.770 --> 00:39:34.580
Not to reconsider the
importance of the Bible,

00:39:34.580 --> 00:39:37.700
the importance of
God or their faith.

00:39:37.700 --> 00:39:39.450
That's just a very
different conversation.

00:39:39.450 --> 00:39:42.600
As you actually have the
privilege, as I've had,

00:39:42.600 --> 00:39:44.680
of being able to take
the time to really do

00:39:44.680 --> 00:39:47.270
your homework before you go
into those conversations,

00:39:47.270 --> 00:39:49.790
a lot of people are just--
it's unprecedented for a lot

00:39:49.790 --> 00:39:50.960
of people.

00:39:50.960 --> 00:39:53.200
And not for the
majority-- at least,

00:39:53.200 --> 00:39:56.860
not initially-- but
for a minority, those

00:39:56.860 --> 00:39:59.020
types of arguments can
change their minds.

00:39:59.020 --> 00:40:00.770
And all you need is a
minority, especially

00:40:00.770 --> 00:40:01.978
within the evangelical world.

00:40:01.978 --> 00:40:04.310
But what does that
word mean, right?

00:40:04.310 --> 00:40:07.550
It's about spreading
the good news.

00:40:07.550 --> 00:40:11.930
So evangelicals love to let
people know what they believe.

00:40:11.930 --> 00:40:14.750
And so, if you can change what
they believe about a topic,

00:40:14.750 --> 00:40:15.894
it's awesome.

00:40:15.894 --> 00:40:17.560
Because then they're
going to let, like,

00:40:17.560 --> 00:40:20.790
1,000 people know about
their new belief about it.

00:40:20.790 --> 00:40:25.690
So that's part of the-- Yeah
it's not easy, it's not fast.

00:40:25.690 --> 00:40:29.780
But it's definitely
possible and worthwhile.

