Slavery, 19 century
America was race-based.

00:46:51.650 --> 00:46:54.060
And it was not, in the same
way, in the first century.

00:46:54.060 --> 00:46:56.890
But slavery in the first
century Rome was brutal.

00:46:56.890 --> 00:46:58.790
I mean, this is not
like, a benign form

00:46:58.790 --> 00:47:01.956
of actually voluntary
servitude for seven years,

00:47:01.956 --> 00:47:03.830
and then you get to go
on and live your life.

00:47:03.830 --> 00:47:04.830
That's not what it was.

00:47:04.830 --> 00:47:06.510
And there's ample
historical evidence

00:47:06.510 --> 00:47:10.570
showing how horrific slavery in
the biblical era actually was.

00:47:10.570 --> 00:47:12.770
So while there are
some differences,

00:47:12.770 --> 00:47:14.620
they're not really--
they don't really

00:47:14.620 --> 00:47:19.650
get to the core of what we find
abhorrent about slavery, today.

00:47:19.650 --> 00:47:24.560
So it's not like what slavery
was changed in a radical way.

00:47:24.560 --> 00:47:29.980
But more Christians became
more empathetic to the cries

00:47:29.980 --> 00:47:31.610
of the oppressed.

00:47:31.610 --> 00:47:35.120
And from a Christian
standpoint, that

00:47:35.120 --> 00:47:37.560
looking at the narrative
arc of scripture,

00:47:37.560 --> 00:47:40.460
so much of which does
focus on the liberation

00:47:40.460 --> 00:47:45.820
of captives, freedom
for the oppressed,

00:47:45.820 --> 00:47:49.390
the kind of radical
dignity that should

00:47:49.390 --> 00:47:54.290
be bestowed upon every person
within a Judeo-Christian

00:47:54.290 --> 00:47:55.000
worldview.

00:47:55.000 --> 00:47:56.750
Not just upon,
like, kings, right?

00:47:56.750 --> 00:48:01.090
But that all people are created
equally in the image of God.

00:48:01.090 --> 00:48:03.970
That should have
these implications

00:48:03.970 --> 00:48:06.140
for how we think
about and how much we

00:48:06.140 --> 00:48:09.240
care about listening to
marginalized and oppressed

00:48:09.240 --> 00:48:10.190
voices.

00:48:10.190 --> 00:48:12.470
Unfortunately, that's
not often been reflected

00:48:12.470 --> 00:48:13.990
in the history of the Church.

00:48:13.990 --> 00:48:18.210
But when the
abolitionist movement

00:48:18.210 --> 00:48:20.990
began to gain traction
in the Church,

00:48:20.990 --> 00:48:24.580
especially in the 19
century, listening-- I mean,

00:48:24.580 --> 00:48:28.280
that type of experience, people
pleading for other people

00:48:28.280 --> 00:48:30.530
to simply look
others in the eyes

00:48:30.530 --> 00:48:32.400
and really consider
their struggles,

00:48:32.400 --> 00:48:34.040
was a big part of that.

00:48:34.040 --> 00:48:36.580
In terms of women's roles--
but at the same time,

00:48:36.580 --> 00:48:39.100
it's never a
sufficient part of it.

00:48:39.100 --> 00:48:41.800
I think that there should
always-- I kind of am torn.

00:48:41.800 --> 00:48:47.020
Because on the one hand, I
think there should generally

00:48:47.020 --> 00:48:51.990
be a bias in favor of
tradition, in the sense

00:48:51.990 --> 00:48:54.581
that, from a
Christian standpoint,

00:48:54.581 --> 00:48:56.330
even though we know
that the tradition got

00:48:56.330 --> 00:49:00.180
a number of important things
wrong-- slavery, heliocentrism,

00:49:00.180 --> 00:49:04.670
the subjugation of
women, anti-semitism--

00:49:04.670 --> 00:49:07.170
the vast majority of things
that Christians recite, like,

00:49:07.170 --> 00:49:09.530
every Sunday in
the creeds, those

00:49:09.530 --> 00:49:11.820
are all part of the
Christian tradition.

00:49:11.820 --> 00:49:14.820
The core things that we believe
about Christian orthodoxy,

00:49:14.820 --> 00:49:18.400
about the trinity, about God,
about Jesus, about Holy Spirit,

00:49:18.400 --> 00:49:20.230
these are all
traditional beliefs.

00:49:20.230 --> 00:49:23.690
And the idea of, if you always
have a bias against tradition,

00:49:23.690 --> 00:49:28.670
it's exhausting at one level
to be constantly throwing up

00:49:28.670 --> 00:49:29.980
in the air all these things.

00:49:29.980 --> 00:49:33.260
But also, there can be a
presumptuousness to it,

00:49:33.260 --> 00:49:34.790
there can be an arrogance to it.

00:49:34.790 --> 00:49:35.320
Not always.

00:49:35.320 --> 00:49:39.300
But there can be, just
assuming that there is not

00:49:39.300 --> 00:49:43.160
great wisdom in-- not just
a generation before you--

00:49:43.160 --> 00:49:45.770
but in generation, after
generation, after generation,

00:49:45.770 --> 00:49:48.530
and all of the wisdom that can
be accumulated through that.

00:49:48.530 --> 00:49:50.780
However, at the
same time, I also

00:49:50.780 --> 00:49:53.330
feel like there should be a
bias in favor of the oppressed.

00:49:53.330 --> 00:49:56.180
And those two things
do clash, right?

00:49:56.180 --> 00:49:59.050
Because a bias in
favor of tradition that

00:49:59.050 --> 00:50:04.160
has no qualifications is
also a bias in favor of well,

00:50:04.160 --> 00:50:08.850
straight, cisgender,
land-owning white men.

00:50:08.850 --> 00:50:10.050
Right?

00:50:10.050 --> 00:50:12.280
And so, how do you
make that balance?

00:50:12.280 --> 00:50:14.550
There's can be a
tendency, then, looking

00:50:14.550 --> 00:50:17.050
at so much of the harm and
oppression it's caused, then,

00:50:17.050 --> 00:50:19.520
to just swing against
tradition entirely.

00:50:19.520 --> 00:50:21.520
And while I'm sympathetic
to why people do that,

00:50:21.520 --> 00:50:25.957
I think that can lead to, well--

00:50:25.957 --> 00:50:27.540
JACK MCCLURE: Another
set of problems.

00:50:27.540 --> 00:50:28.956
MATTHEW VINES:
Yeah, it just leads

00:50:28.956 --> 00:50:32.040
to an entirely
different set of issues

00:50:32.040 --> 00:50:34.390
that I'm not really sure
are the key to liberation

00:50:34.390 --> 00:50:35.792
for oppressed peoples.

00:50:35.792 --> 00:50:37.875
So it's kind of like holding
those things tension.

00:50:37.875 --> 00:50:39.440
So I would say, like,
I think they experience

00:50:39.440 --> 00:50:40.610
paradigm matters a lot.

00:50:40.610 --> 00:50:43.020
But because I think that
tradition matters a lot,

00:50:43.020 --> 00:50:45.280
because I think
that scripture has

00:50:45.280 --> 00:50:48.010
to be-- because I think that
the authority of scripture

00:50:48.010 --> 00:50:49.170
matters a lot.

00:50:49.170 --> 00:50:51.460
You kind of have to hold
those things in tension.

00:50:51.460 --> 00:50:53.250
So with something
like women's roles,

00:50:53.250 --> 00:50:55.450
you can definitely make
the case from experience.

00:50:55.450 --> 00:50:57.450
I mean, this is what we
see in the book of Acts,

00:50:57.450 --> 00:51:03.950
where they say, look, we know
that you don't think Gentiles

00:51:03.950 --> 00:51:05.360
can be part of God's people.

00:51:05.360 --> 00:51:07.710
But we see the
fruit-- we see them.

00:51:07.710 --> 00:51:09.680
We see the fruit of
the spirit, right.

00:51:09.680 --> 00:51:13.690
And we see that they have
the spirit at work in them.

00:51:13.690 --> 00:51:18.770
Therefore, they can be part
of the Christian community.

00:51:18.770 --> 00:51:21.060
So that was a pretty
experienced-based argument.

00:51:21.060 --> 00:51:23.035
And so people, certainly, you
can make that type of argument

00:51:23.035 --> 00:51:25.200
about saying, look, we
see women who are serving

00:51:25.200 --> 00:51:26.199
in leadership positions.

00:51:26.199 --> 00:51:30.290
We see all these gift that they
are offering to the church.

00:51:30.290 --> 00:51:33.190
We see their ministries
being blessed, or something.

00:51:33.190 --> 00:51:35.300
At the same time,
you want to buttress

00:51:35.300 --> 00:51:36.790
that, you want to
supplement that

00:51:36.790 --> 00:51:38.600
with making a scriptural
case, as well,

00:51:38.600 --> 00:51:42.290
for, here is where
we see movement

00:51:42.290 --> 00:51:45.920
in scripture toward women
occupying more leadership

00:51:45.920 --> 00:51:50.610
positions, or toward greater
equality in roles for men

00:51:50.610 --> 00:51:51.900
women, those sorts of things.

00:51:51.900 --> 00:51:53.832
So I think it's
like a both, and.

00:51:53.832 --> 00:51:55.290
AUDIENCE: This is
a little bit more

00:51:55.290 --> 00:51:57.104
of sort of a personal question.

00:51:57.104 --> 00:51:59.020
So you can decide how
personal you want to be.

00:51:59.020 --> 00:52:00.820
But for me, one
of the challenges

00:52:00.820 --> 00:52:02.780
of being gay and
Christian, I spent

00:52:02.780 --> 00:52:04.230
a lot of time kind
of reconciling

00:52:04.230 --> 00:52:05.260
how I could be both.

00:52:05.260 --> 00:52:07.340
And I wish I had had
your book 10 years ago.

00:52:07.340 --> 00:52:09.219
But now, one of the
things that I actually

00:52:09.219 --> 00:52:10.760
shared with my pastor
a few weeks ago

00:52:10.760 --> 00:52:14.090
was struggling with how to
be gay and Christian in 2015,

00:52:14.090 --> 00:52:15.150
in San Francisco.

00:52:15.150 --> 00:52:18.140
And so, there's so many
cultural norms around sexuality,

00:52:18.140 --> 00:52:18.970
for example.

00:52:18.970 --> 00:52:21.670
And it's sort of a gay
stereotype where you have sex,

00:52:21.670 --> 00:52:23.340
and then you go
on the first date.

00:52:23.340 --> 00:52:27.410
And so, how do you think
about other teachings

00:52:27.410 --> 00:52:30.000
around sexuality, around
how we express that.

00:52:30.000 --> 00:52:34.550
And how do you kind of live
a godly, Christian life

00:52:34.550 --> 00:52:39.410
in the context of a culture
that is highly sexualized?

00:52:39.410 --> 00:52:41.810
MATTHEW VINES: Yeah, that's
a really good question.

00:52:41.810 --> 00:52:43.510
I would say my
first answer to it

00:52:43.510 --> 00:52:46.270
is, the way that I approach that
is that it's really sensitive.

00:52:46.270 --> 00:52:50.040
And so, I am always--
especially issues

00:52:50.040 --> 00:52:53.630
around sex and
sexual ethics, when

00:52:53.630 --> 00:52:56.550
you are talking about a
community of people that

00:52:56.550 --> 00:53:02.200
has been rejected by
the church, there just

00:53:02.200 --> 00:53:07.250
has to be so much sensitivity
around that and a lot of grace

00:53:07.250 --> 00:53:07.830
around that.

00:53:07.830 --> 00:53:13.870
I think that really conservative
Christians, in particular,

00:53:13.870 --> 00:53:16.710
if they want to say all same-sex
relationships are wrong,

00:53:16.710 --> 00:53:20.380
and they want to offer no
support for LGBT people living

00:53:20.380 --> 00:53:23.860
out hope for their
relational future--

00:53:23.860 --> 00:53:27.530
a romantic future or
family-- then what

00:53:27.530 --> 00:53:30.750
place do they really have to
criticize people who they think

00:53:30.750 --> 00:53:33.440
aren't living in a sufficiently
chased way, or something.

00:53:33.440 --> 00:53:36.230
Because it's like, look,
you're offering people nothing.

00:53:36.230 --> 00:53:39.970
And then just going
to condemn them

00:53:39.970 --> 00:53:43.820
when they're just trying to
find their own way in the world.

00:53:43.820 --> 00:53:46.030
So I'm very sympathetic to that.

00:53:46.030 --> 00:53:47.850
At the same time,
I think that that's

00:53:47.850 --> 00:53:50.480
a totally non-ideal situation.

00:53:50.480 --> 00:53:54.040
Ideally, you shouldn't
have millions

00:53:54.040 --> 00:53:57.750
of gay kids being rejected by
their Christian families, all

00:53:57.750 --> 00:54:00.130
of the world, in
the name of Jesus.

00:54:00.130 --> 00:54:03.100
And then made two loath
themselves and loath

00:54:03.100 --> 00:54:05.552
their sexuality, and
then seek to swing

00:54:05.552 --> 00:54:07.010
the pendulum in
the other direction

00:54:07.010 --> 00:54:09.387
by totally embracing
every potential aspect

00:54:09.387 --> 00:54:11.470
of your sexuality you could
conceive of for, like,

00:54:11.470 --> 00:54:12.490
five years and then
getting tired of it.

00:54:12.490 --> 00:54:14.480
And then swinging it back
to the middle, right.

00:54:14.480 --> 00:54:16.320
That's not really ideal.

00:54:16.320 --> 00:54:18.580
So what I'm trying
to do is twofold.

00:54:18.580 --> 00:54:20.110
One is the pastoral
lens, which is

00:54:20.110 --> 00:54:23.060
about how much grace and
sensitivity you have to have.

00:54:23.060 --> 00:54:26.140
And you just can't
preach at people.

00:54:26.140 --> 00:54:27.045
You have to listen.

00:54:27.045 --> 00:54:28.420
You have to build
a relationship.

00:54:28.420 --> 00:54:31.660
You have to be willing to
learn and grow from people.

00:54:31.660 --> 00:54:33.190
But that's the pastoral lens.

00:54:33.190 --> 00:54:36.450
Then there's also this kind of
theological or doctrinal lens,

00:54:36.450 --> 00:54:38.510
which is the
question of, ideally,

00:54:38.510 --> 00:54:40.480
what should the
church be teaching?

00:54:40.480 --> 00:54:43.760
And even though there has to be
a whole lot of space and grace

00:54:43.760 --> 00:54:47.660
in the midst of recovering
from, really, the church's

00:54:47.660 --> 00:54:52.900
sins against the
LGBT community, what

00:54:52.900 --> 00:54:55.730
would be the theological ideal?

00:54:55.730 --> 00:55:00.110
And so, the ideal that I
present-- and so, basically, I

00:55:00.110 --> 00:55:03.460
grew up being taught
that sex is for marriage.

00:55:03.460 --> 00:55:05.580
And I never really had
an issue with that.

00:55:05.580 --> 00:55:09.774
So from when I-- when I learned
about sex-- however old I was.

00:55:09.774 --> 00:55:10.690
I don't even remember.

00:55:10.690 --> 00:55:11.800
I was just, like, all right.

00:55:11.800 --> 00:55:13.633
That's something I'll
do when I get married.

00:55:13.633 --> 00:55:16.272
It's going to be great, and
never really thought about it.

00:55:16.272 --> 00:55:17.980
I mean, not that I
didn't think about it.

00:55:17.980 --> 00:55:20.060
I'm saying I never
thought about-- that

00:55:20.060 --> 00:55:22.120
was never a source of
stress for me, or anything.

00:55:22.120 --> 00:55:23.640
That was something
I wanted to do.

00:55:23.640 --> 00:55:27.279
And it was just a part
of who I wanted to be

00:55:27.279 --> 00:55:28.320
and how I wanted to live.

00:55:28.320 --> 00:55:31.430
And so, when I realized that I
was gay, I was just like, well,

00:55:31.430 --> 00:55:35.357
I don't really want to
radically change who I am.

00:55:35.357 --> 00:55:36.940
I don't think being
gay should require

00:55:36.940 --> 00:55:41.282
you to overturn value systems
that are important to you.

00:55:41.282 --> 00:55:42.740
And so, I was like,
well, honestly,

00:55:42.740 --> 00:55:45.870
I just want to live
in the same way

00:55:45.870 --> 00:55:48.530
that I would if I
hadn't been gay.

00:55:48.530 --> 00:55:50.310
Is there the same
support for it?

00:55:50.310 --> 00:55:51.940
Not really.

00:55:51.940 --> 00:55:54.170
But that's what
I'm always seeking

00:55:54.170 --> 00:55:56.840
to live into-- oftentimes
in Christian theology,

00:55:56.840 --> 00:56:00.130
there's this conversation around
the already and the not yet,

00:56:00.130 --> 00:56:02.100
right, around eschatology.

00:56:02.100 --> 00:56:04.970
And that's like the
end times theology.

00:56:04.970 --> 00:56:07.130
But also just the
question of, we're

00:56:07.130 --> 00:56:09.230
living into this
new creation that's

00:56:09.230 --> 00:56:12.660
been inaugurated by Jesus
in which all things will

00:56:12.660 --> 00:56:15.820
be redeemed, and all
things will be made new.

00:56:15.820 --> 00:56:16.940
But we're not there yet.

00:56:16.940 --> 00:56:18.110
And so there's that tension.

00:56:18.110 --> 00:56:19.810
But I think we need
some people who

00:56:19.810 --> 00:56:23.200
are seeking to live
into the not-yet,

00:56:23.200 --> 00:56:24.810
or seeking to live
into-- seeking

00:56:24.810 --> 00:56:29.650
to bring more of the
not-yet into the already.

00:56:29.650 --> 00:56:32.920
In the sense of,
if I want churches

00:56:32.920 --> 00:56:35.940
to be creating the
support system for people

00:56:35.940 --> 00:56:39.755
like me to be able to pursue
a relationship in a family

00:56:39.755 --> 00:56:43.060
in the same way that we thought
we could back when we didn't

00:56:43.060 --> 00:56:45.800
realize we were gay,
then we're going

00:56:45.800 --> 00:56:50.000
to need some people who are
just living into-- living

00:56:50.000 --> 00:56:52.040
in the anticipation of that.

00:56:52.040 --> 00:56:54.780
And so, that's why that is
still how I want to live.

00:56:54.780 --> 00:56:57.020
And I think that there are
good theological reasons

00:56:57.020 --> 00:57:02.340
for that being and ideal that
I sort of discuss in the book.

00:57:02.340 --> 00:57:04.980
And I hope that by--
and I know there

00:57:04.980 --> 00:57:09.072
are a number of gay Christians
who feel the same way.

00:57:09.072 --> 00:57:11.530
But there are plenty of people
who don't feel the same way.

00:57:11.530 --> 00:57:13.104
And other gay
Christians-- or maybe

00:57:13.104 --> 00:57:15.270
did feel the same, feel
it's practically impossible,

00:57:15.270 --> 00:57:16.210
or something.

00:57:16.210 --> 00:57:18.790
And so, that's why
people-- I just

00:57:18.790 --> 00:57:21.730
feel like there's been enough
of a kind of shame-based culture

00:57:21.730 --> 00:57:24.840
around these topics that I'm
much more interested in saying,

00:57:24.840 --> 00:57:28.960
look-- especially for people
who are LGBT Christians.

00:57:28.960 --> 00:57:31.820
I think people
should do their best.

00:57:31.820 --> 00:57:34.090
Strive to do your best.

00:57:34.090 --> 00:57:35.590
Do the best that you can.

00:57:35.590 --> 00:57:40.740
And that's going to look
different for different people.

00:57:40.740 --> 00:57:43.490
Our goal is to be
modeling and showing,

00:57:43.490 --> 00:57:47.899
like, this is what really
positive, meaningful

00:57:47.899 --> 00:57:49.440
same-sex relationships
can look like.

00:57:49.440 --> 00:57:51.559
And so, I want people
to do their best

00:57:51.559 --> 00:57:52.600
to seek to live that out.

00:57:52.600 --> 00:57:54.916
But sometimes people's
relationships will fail,

00:57:54.916 --> 00:57:56.790
or they're going to
really bad relationships.

00:57:56.790 --> 00:57:59.800
And there's no need for people
to feel like overwhelming shame

00:57:59.800 --> 00:58:01.400
about that.

00:58:01.400 --> 00:58:05.875
I just think it is helpful when
we have some gay Christians who

00:58:05.875 --> 00:58:08.807
have enough support, or
are just able to live more

00:58:08.807 --> 00:58:09.890
into anticipation of that.

00:58:09.890 --> 00:58:11.431
To be able to model
for people, like,

00:58:11.431 --> 00:58:13.190
this is what an option could be.

00:58:13.190 --> 00:58:17.160
And then to be able to present
that model in a much more non

00:58:17.160 --> 00:58:20.240
in-your-face, non
you-must-do-this or we're going

00:58:20.240 --> 00:58:21.930
to bang a hammer
over your head way.

00:58:21.930 --> 00:58:26.954
But I would have just loved to
have seen actual role models

00:58:26.954 --> 00:58:28.120
doing that, when I came out.

00:58:28.120 --> 00:58:29.620
To say, I knew
that's what I wanted,

00:58:29.620 --> 00:58:32.100
but I couldn't find anybody
who's doing that, right.

00:58:32.100 --> 00:58:36.690
And so, it's still
kind of a tiny niche.

00:58:36.690 --> 00:58:39.870
But that's at least how
I'm seeking to approach it.

00:58:39.870 --> 00:58:41.440
But I also think
that there has to be

00:58:41.440 --> 00:58:46.770
a lot of grace in
light of how much harm

00:58:46.770 --> 00:58:51.527
the church has directly
done on these very topics.

00:58:51.527 --> 00:58:53.110
AUDIENCE: Have you
had much experience

00:58:53.110 --> 00:58:56.780
talking with Christians who are
not evangelicals, or perhaps

00:58:56.780 --> 00:58:59.030
from traditions that are
far away from your own?

00:58:59.030 --> 00:59:01.055
Maybe Christians from
the orthodox tradition

00:59:01.055 --> 00:59:03.390
or far afield from your own?

00:59:03.390 --> 00:59:05.780
And is there any difference
in the sorts of conversations

00:59:05.780 --> 00:59:07.167
you have with them?

00:59:07.167 --> 00:59:09.000
MATTHEW VINES: There
is a lot of difference.

00:59:09.000 --> 00:59:10.940
And so, most of the
conversations I have

00:59:10.940 --> 00:59:15.290
will kind of be
in my wheelhouse.

00:59:15.290 --> 00:59:20.450
Theologically, I try not to
overstep my bounds, too much.

00:59:20.450 --> 00:59:25.000
So I'm much more interested
in a meeting-- for instance,

00:59:25.000 --> 00:59:28.080
when it comes to Catholics, I'm
much more interested in meeting

00:59:28.080 --> 00:59:32.080
other LGBT Catholics
who are interested in

00:59:32.080 --> 00:59:34.610
and who care about
reforming their church,

00:59:34.610 --> 00:59:39.144
and helping equip them with--
I mean, the scriptures are not

00:59:39.144 --> 00:59:41.310
identical, of course, for
Catholics and Protestants.

00:59:41.310 --> 00:59:43.440
But on this issue,
the scriptural issues

00:59:43.440 --> 00:59:45.420
are pretty much the same.

00:59:45.420 --> 00:59:47.880
Of course, Catholics
have additional layers

00:59:47.880 --> 00:59:53.190
of theological discourse
around all issues.

00:59:53.190 --> 00:59:54.950
So there are important
areas of overlap.

00:59:54.950 --> 00:59:56.991
So I'm interested in
building those relationships

00:59:56.991 --> 00:59:59.410
and helping to equip
people in those contexts

00:59:59.410 --> 01:00:02.137
with a lot of the scriptural
resources that they need.

01:00:02.137 --> 01:00:03.720
But then, they're
really going to have

01:00:03.720 --> 01:00:06.320
to be the ones who take that
and run with it-- in terms

01:00:06.320 --> 01:00:08.870
of tailoring it to their
specific environment

01:00:08.870 --> 01:00:13.710
and denomination or theological
context, adding to it,

01:00:13.710 --> 01:00:15.770
refining it, adapting it.

01:00:15.770 --> 01:00:18.950
So I am rarely going
to be the person

01:00:18.950 --> 01:00:21.800
having-- in terms of a lot of
the conversations that I have,

01:00:21.800 --> 01:00:26.680
it's mostly going to be with
Protestant evangelical pastors

01:00:26.680 --> 01:00:27.810
and leaders.

01:00:27.810 --> 01:00:32.260
And once you get
to other contexts--

01:00:32.260 --> 01:00:36.540
I don't want to be trying
to represent people

01:00:36.540 --> 01:00:38.920
when I know that there
are other people who

01:00:38.920 --> 01:00:41.350
know a lot more about their
particular context than I do.

01:00:41.350 --> 01:00:43.320
So that's why I want to be just
building those relationships,

01:00:43.320 --> 01:00:45.740
seeking to equip and empower
to the extent that I can,

01:00:45.740 --> 01:00:47.430
to the extent that
it makes sense.

01:00:47.430 --> 01:00:51.920
But then, letting LGBT
Catholics or LGBT Orthodox

01:00:51.920 --> 01:00:55.864
Christians really take
the initiative on that.

01:00:55.864 --> 01:00:57.530
And so, then, the
last thing I would say

01:00:57.530 --> 01:01:01.460
is, that is a lot of what we do
with the Reformation Project,

01:01:01.460 --> 01:01:04.380
is bringing people from a
wide variety of backgrounds,

01:01:04.380 --> 01:01:09.440
equip them with these scriptural
resources and arguments.

01:01:09.440 --> 01:01:12.030
But then allow that
and seek to help them

01:01:12.030 --> 01:01:14.349
and empower them, as
they are the best people

01:01:14.349 --> 01:01:15.515
in their particular context.

01:01:15.515 --> 01:01:17.390
So we're doing a conference.

01:01:17.390 --> 01:01:19.660
Our next big conference is
in Kansas City, November 5

01:01:19.660 --> 01:01:20.243
through the 7.

01:01:20.243 --> 01:01:22.880
And we're doing one in
LA, actually, next year.

01:01:22.880 --> 01:01:24.630
So if you're interested,
you can follow us

01:01:24.630 --> 01:01:25.882
on Facebook or Twitter.

01:01:25.882 --> 01:01:27.340
You can sign up
for the conferences

01:01:27.340 --> 01:01:29.005
at reformationproject.org.

01:01:29.005 --> 01:01:31.320
Or if you can't go but you
know family or friends you

01:01:31.320 --> 01:01:33.480
think would benefit from
it, you should send them.

01:01:33.480 --> 01:01:36.310
Because it's really
sort of a great melting

01:01:36.310 --> 01:01:39.180
pot of traditions.

01:01:39.180 --> 01:01:40.860
And even though
the dominant group

01:01:40.860 --> 01:01:42.740
there would still probably
be evangelical Protestants.

01:01:42.740 --> 01:01:45.198
Of course, we have Catholics
and Orthodox Christians there,

01:01:45.198 --> 01:01:48.980
as well, who can really enrich
our understandings, too.

01:01:48.980 --> 01:01:50.900
JACK MCCLURE: Thanks
for that question.

01:01:50.900 --> 01:01:53.240
Thank you for being
with us today.

01:01:53.240 --> 01:01:55.590
I really appreciate the
integrity of the bring

01:01:55.590 --> 01:01:58.850
to the conversation, because
you're open to other ideas,

01:01:58.850 --> 01:02:02.675
instead of being here to kind
of forcing anything on anybody.

01:02:02.675 --> 01:02:04.050
I appreciate that,
and especially

01:02:04.050 --> 01:02:07.040
from a perspective that's a
little different, in terms

01:02:07.040 --> 01:02:08.750
of our trying to understand.

01:02:08.750 --> 01:02:11.340
But I think every
congregation, everybody

01:02:11.340 --> 01:02:14.420
is really coming together
in real interesting ways.

01:02:14.420 --> 01:02:16.136
At least we're
having a discussion.

01:02:16.136 --> 01:02:18.260
And I appreciate that you
want a discussion and not

01:02:18.260 --> 01:02:21.405
an argument or a
fisticuffs, you know.

01:02:21.405 --> 01:02:22.280
MATTHEW VINES: Right.

01:02:22.280 --> 01:02:24.280
JACK MCCLURE: Thanks very
much for bringing that

01:02:24.280 --> 01:02:25.250
to the conversation.

01:02:25.250 --> 01:02:27.230
And with you, I am appreciative.

01:02:27.230 --> 01:02:28.420
Aren't you, as well?

01:02:28.420 --> 01:02:29.420
So, thank you.

01:02:29.420 --> 01:02:29.920
[APPLAUSE]

01:02:29.920 --> 01:02:32.070
MATTHEW VINES: Well,
thank you so much.

